          <p style="text-align: left;">&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;<img src="https://gujaratvidyapith.org/gujaratvidyapith.org/newsite/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/ngvplogo.jpg" loading="lazy" data-original-title="" title="" aria-describedby="tooltip599979"/><br/></p>
          <p>
            <br/>
          </p>
          <p>The emblem of the GUJARAT VIDYAPITH is an open lotus flower. In it, in Devanagari script, is written “<em><strong>Sa vidya ya vimuktaye</strong></em>” i.e. knowledge is that which liberates (us). In Arabic is written “<em><strong>al hikamato zallatual monimine fahaiso uajedaha ahakko leha.</strong></em>”</p>
          <p>In this emblem there is a Banyan tree i.e. Ficus benghalensis, which signifies growth. There is also the moon that symbolizes beauty, calmness and development. Lotus shows non-attachment, holy spirit. Lamps on either side in a circle symbolize knowledge.</p>
          <p>The Gujarat Vidyapith was established for attachment of independence. The object of political independence was temporary but the devotion for self-liberation and knowledge are our permanent ideals. This devotion should continue to grow like a banyan tree and moon with a spirit of non-attachment of a lotus.</p>
